# Docker

## Required

- All services run as a **non-root user** (`trader`, `api`, `nextjs`).
- Production images do not contain dev dependencies (separate dev/prod
  layers or `--no-dev` install).
- Each Dockerfile installs project deps, then copies code, then sets the
  user — in that order — so layer caching works.
- Python service images build from the shared local `trading-base` image.
  Build it with `python dev.py base` before local service builds (same as
  `docker build -f Dockerfile.base -t trading-base .`). CI builds
  `trading-base:latest` as the first step of the `docker` job in
  `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (same runner as backend/engine). On `main`
  pushes that touch `Dockerfile.base` or `pyproject.toml`, the
  `trading-base.yml` workflow publishes
  `ghcr.io/<owner>/trading-lab-base:<sha>|:latest` and writes a `:cache`
  ref via `cache-to: type=registry`. PR runs do **not** read that cache
  (see "CI multi-step buildx" below).
- Healthchecks are defined in `docker-compose.yml` for `redis`, `backend`,
  and `frontend`. The trading-engine container has a process-level liveness
  check via the orchestrator.
- The `trading-net` network is `external: true`. The host already runs
  `ollama` and `hermes` on it (see [`docs/INFRASTRUCTURE.md`](mdc:docs/INFRASTRUCTURE.md)).

## Windows Docker Desktop dev loop

When bind-mounting the repo on Windows/WSL2, never expose host-only dependency
or cache directories inside `/app`. `docker-compose.dev.yml` must mask:
`.venv`, `.git`, `.mypy_cache`, `.ruff_cache`, `.pytest_cache`, `.deepeval`,
`agent-transcripts`, `frontend/node_modules`, `frontend/.next`, and
`trading_lab.egg-info`.

Measured consequence from 2026-04-26: without masks, `/app` exposed ~3 GB and
pytest collection took 15+ minutes; with masks, `/app` was ~5.7 MB and the
inner-loop unit suite passed in ~53 seconds.

## CI multi-step buildx (`FROM <local-image>` chains)

The `docker` job builds `trading-base` and then `engine` / `backend` /
`frontend`, each via `docker/build-push-action@v6` with `load: true`.
Several plausible-looking shapes for this **do not work**; PR #17 burned
five iterations before landing the working one. The current shape is:

- `docker/setup-buildx-action@v3` with `driver: docker` (host BuildKit,
  shares the image store with the local Docker daemon).
- No `cache-from` / `cache-to`. `trading-base` is rebuilt from cold pip
  install on every PR run (~3-5 min). Acceptable until a warm path is
  designed.

Lessons (do not repeat in this repo):

- The default `docker-container` buildx driver runs BuildKit in its own
  container with an isolated image store. `load: true` writes to the
  host Docker daemon, but the next buildx step in the same container
  cannot see it; `FROM trading-base` then resolves via `docker.io` and
  401s. Solution: `driver: docker` for these multi-step chains.
- `cache-from: type=registry,ref=…/trading-lab-base:cache` aborts the
  build on **both** 403 (unauthenticated) and 404 (cache miss). There
  is no soft-miss mode. `ignore-error=true` is **not** a real BuildKit
  option (silently ignored). Adding `docker/login-action@v3` only
  converts 403 → 404, which still aborts.
- `build-contexts: trading-base=docker-image://trading-base:latest`
  does **not** redirect resolution to the local Docker daemon — it still
  resolves via the registry. It is not a substitute for the `docker`
  driver here.
- `driver: docker` does not support `cache-from/to: type=gha`. That
  cost is intentional; the alternative (re-introducing
  `docker-container` plus a working warm-cache path) cost more cycles in
  PR #17 than the cold rebuild costs per PR.

Trade-offs that **are** acceptable to revisit later, in their own PR:

- Switching back to `docker-container` and using `cache-from:
  type=registry,ref=…:cache` once `trading-base.yml` has populated the
  ref on `main`. The fundamentals above will still apply: BuildKit must
  be authenticated (registry creds), the ref must already exist, and
  cross-step `FROM <local>` chains will need an alternate source of
  truth (e.g. push intermediates to a local registry on the runner).

## Hostnames inside the network

Containers address each other by **service name**, never `localhost`:

| From → To           | URL                          |
|---------------------|------------------------------|
| frontend → backend  | `http://backend:8000`        |
| backend → redis     | `redis://redis:6379/0`       |
| any → ollama        | `http://ollama:11434`        |
| any → DuckDB volume | `/data/market.duckdb`        |

## Forbidden

- Running as root in production stages.
- Baking secrets into images. `.env` is mounted at runtime.
- Hard-coded `localhost` URLs in container code.
- Calling `docker compose up` from a hook (the user does this).
- Removing dev bind-mount masks without replacing them with an equivalent
  Windows-safe strategy.

## Build verification

Every Dockerfile change must be followed by:
```bash
docker compose build <service>
docker compose up -d <service> && docker compose logs --tail 50 <service>
```
CI builds all three images on every PR.
